and altered mental status","Fever, headache, and neck stiffness","Fever, neck stiffness, and seizures","Headache, photophobia, and vomiting"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classic triad of meningitis symptoms consists of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFever\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeadache\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck stiffness\u003C/strong\u003E (nuchal rigidity)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese symptoms occur due to inflammation of the meninges. However, it\u0027s important to note that all three symptoms are present in less than 50% of cases. The absence of the complete triad should not rule out the diagnosis if clinical suspicion exists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFever, headache, and photophobia\u003C/strong\u003E - While common in meningitis, photophobia is not part of the classic triad\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeadache, neck stiffness, and altered mental status\u003C/strong\u003E - Altered mental status is a concerning sign but not part of the classic triad\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFever, neck stiffness, and seizures\u003C/strong\u003E - Seizures are a complication rather than part of the classic presentation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeadache, photophobia, and vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E - These symptoms are common but do not represent the classic triad\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important symptoms and signs of meningitis include confusion, drowsiness, rash (particularly in meningococcal disease), photophobia, and vomiting. The diagnosis should be considered in any patient with concerning symptoms, even if the classic triad is not present, as early recognition and treatment are crucial for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The classic triad of meningitis consists of fever, headache, and neck stiffness, though all three are present in less than 50% of cases.","Additional symptoms such as photophobia, altered mental status, and seizures may be present but are not part of the classic triad.","The absence of the classic triad does not rule out meningitis."],"references":["Hersi K, Gonzalez FJ, Kondamudi NP. Meningitis. [Updated 2023 Aug 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459360/","Hasbun R. Progress and Challenges in Bacterial Meningitis: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Dec 6;328(21):2147-2154. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.20521. Erratum in: JAMA. 2023 Feb 14;329(6):515. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.0570. PMID: 36472590.","Young N, Thomas M. Meningitis in adults: diagnosis and management. Intern Med J. 2018 Nov;48(11):1294-1307. doi: 10.1111/imj.14102. PMID: 30387309."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T21:10:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T21:12:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9870"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70170"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships"